Rapid climate change, especially the rapid cooling and warming that occur at the beginning and end of glaciation cycles, is always accompanied by the extinction of populations that fail to track climate shift or adapt to new conditions (e.g., 
 Hofreiter & Stewart, 2009; 
 Loarie et al., 2009; 
 Corlett & Westcott, 2013). Therefore, aggravated by the risk of failure of tracking and adaptation, the drastic range shrinkage of 
 P. amabilis may have once placed this species near extinction.
